<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title></title></head><body><div><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">RCH0011</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> by Jonathan Stanley for the Independent Children’s Homes Association (ICHA). </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The ICHA is the largest independent children’s homes membership organisation. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It provides evidence-based and informed policy and practice leadership for the sector. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We wish to ensure the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ommittee has the evidence and experience that supports the consistent views of providers. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Much of what is being taken </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in the debate </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">as conventional wisdom</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">has not been given rigorous scrutiny. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Sensationalist media interpretation and reporting needs to be set aside in favour of robust analysis of the evidence and to uphold the cardinal principle held by all stakeholders: ‘the right placement at the right time for the right child at the right cost.’</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">I would be happy to give evidence in person to the Committee.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The person making this submission</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Jonathan Stanley, the Chief Executive Officer of the ICHA, has 40 years of working in residential child care across local authority, voluntary and independent sectors, managing residential and associated integrated provision (education, care, health) for national resources that address the learning, emotional, and social needs of young people. He is Principal Partner of the National Centre for Excellence in Residential Child Care. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">He was a member of the work groups for the DfE regarding the reform of residential child care. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Even with the pref</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">erence for family and community-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">based placements</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> the numbers of children requiring a children’s home remains consistent year on year </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(page 6 DfE data pack September 2013)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">:</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a href="http://media.education.gov.uk/assets/files/pdf/c/childrens%20homes%20data%20pack%202013.PDF"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://media.education.gov.uk/assets/files/pdf/c/childrens homes data pack2013.PDF</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The DfE current proposals can be supported</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in principle but much more definition is needed and they do not form the necessary comprehensive change that will result in a change to the positive use of children’s homes. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There are obstacles being presented to children’s homes as they seek to change location. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We do not have enough robust evidence or experience to make authoritative decisions for the future of residential child care. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is still too much missing from the proposals; a cohesive national strategy; a new direction for commissioning; audits of need should lead to dialogue and development locally, regionally, and nationally. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A graded, sequential, hierarchical view of care may not be in the best interests of young people.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We can use residential options in more diverse ways and we should not limit the potential responses for young people</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Leadership is needed portraying children’s homes as a positive choice supporting the many young people who state a preference for residential placement.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Quality of homes – 72% Good or Better – and more to be done</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The DfE data pack dispels several myths that have gained credence regarding size, location, ownership</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">deprivation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The DfE data pack raises concerns </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and questions as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to age, number of previous placements, length of stay. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">‘Felt security’ is the indicator needed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Is a local or national perspective needed? </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">No one knows the proportion of local placements needed.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> It is certainly not 100%. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We must ensure specialism, safety and choice and these cannot always be available locally.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Accurate costings of placements are available – Local Authority £2490: non-statutory £2841</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Section One - The proposed changes can be supported in principle</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63.82pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Providers, local authorities and Government are united in one aim: ‘the right placement at the right time for the right child at the right cost.’</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63.82pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The ICHA supports the proposed changes in principle. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63.82pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The proposed changes do not represent the necessary comprehensi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ve change of children’s services</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that will result in a positive use of children’s homes. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We fear that the damaging sequential and hierarchical ‘last resort’ use of residential child care could continue.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63.82pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is an urgent need for definition and clarity on many aspects</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> such as Out of Authority (can currently mean round the corner, over the road) and safe area (local authorit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ies tell providers they need G</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">overnment guidance).</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 63.82pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Some changes address practices that should already be operating and the responsibility of others is to be loaded on to children’s homes, for example, notification of a child being placed in a home by another local authority </span></li></ol></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Section two – The need for more evidence</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63.82pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">On the current level of understanding, gleaned from evidence to date, its analysis and interpretation, it is unlikely that we have anywhere near enough unassailable evidence or experience to make authoritative decisions for the future of residential child care. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Government must invest in research. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Society's current level of understanding encourages simplified rather than sophisticated analysis. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 63.82pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The SSDA903 annual return from local authorities is increasingly accepted as insufficiently robust.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> If it is to be a reliable foundation for policy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> there must be revision of the data targeted. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The guidance needs revision to ensure the same information is given by all local authorities. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Equally there are other robust sources that can and should be used.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Section three - too much is missing from the proposals</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">A national strategy</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 63.82pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The focus on immediate concerns obstructs progress towards a cohesive national strategy for residential child care that stretches from identification, assessment, planning and placement to evaluation that would deliver the ‘most appropriate placement’ for every child. </span></li></ol></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">A new direction and role for commissioning</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 63.82pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There must be a new direction for commissioning. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The new DfE data pack states that the market is ‘not responding so that supply matches demand.’ </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sector is providing what local authorities ask of it.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Immense time and money has been expended in ‘market making’ and 'shaping’. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The recent OPM/LGA report </span><a href="http://www.local.gov.uk/c/document_library/get_file?uuid=a20bf422-5640-43cc-afc6-7ab6ca3a59ec&amp;groupId=10180"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.local.gov.uk/c/document_library/get_file?uuid=a20bf422-5640-43cc-afc6-7ab6ca3a59ec&amp;groupId=10180</span></a><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">highlights practice that is more effective than others</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">yet it has man</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">y recommendations that lead to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">questioning current arrangements and how they heighten effective care and cost management. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A change in commissioning is needed solely from weighting cost over care considerations to creating the necessary data and analysis. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">All local authorities should undertake an audit of need using the same methodology</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">These can be aggregated to plan sufficient and diverse provision – 'the right placement at the right time for the right child at the right cost.’ </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">With data open to providers and dialogue, there can be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sufficient, diverse and sustainable homes locally, sub-regionally, regionally and nationally and with a level playing field for local authority and non-statutory homes. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Each home could have its specialism so we do not continue with the serial use of fostering, then in-house homes before being able to receive the care in a home matched to needs.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The matching of need to placement is not being achieved to a universally high degree. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Whilst homes will strengthen their Statement of Purpose, local authorities must take notice of the independent research finding of the need for better Placement Request Forms</span></li></ol></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 67.65pt; text-align:justify"><a href="http://www.icha.org.uk/uploads/files/use_of_placement_request_forms_in_commissioningplacements_for_lac_final.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.icha.org.uk/uploads/files/use_of_placement_request_forms_in_commissioningplacements_for_lac_final.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The consequences of seeing children’s homes only as ‘high cost’ and how constructing a graded, sequential, hierarchical view of care may not b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">e in the best interest</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> of young people.</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We have used children’s homes in more diverse ways than now. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We can again have homes that are community-based, offering support and acting as hubs of care. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Some examples are already operating. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We need to appreciate that children’s homes can offer environments that are both generalist</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and universalist offering substitute, supplemental, or alternative care for family-based options</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as well as the specialisms we know we need. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is concerning that the opening pages of the DfE data pack exclude such ideas.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 67.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is a social and political choice as to how we use our homes. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We use children’s homes as an intervention rather than for upbringing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as we did before, and which European neighbours still do. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The diversity of needs and preferences suggest we need to do both and anything less is to limit the response to young people and not be child-centred. </span></li></ol></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Residential child care as a positive option for young people</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There has been a noticeable lack of political leadership for children’s homes to be portrayed as a positive choice. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is not enough to deny a hierarchy of placements. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Explaining that sometimes a children’s home is exactly ‘the right placement at the right time for the right child’ is vital.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Media imbalance and sensationalism obscure the fact that we have world class provision.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 67.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It must be recalled that reports over years of young people’s views say that many prefer residential placement.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Section three - Addressing specific issues and the DfE data pack</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Quality of homes – 72% Good or Better – and more to be done</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:14.4pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There has been a focus on quality and the creation of a perception that homes are ‘failing.’ </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The reference that must be used is official statistics from Ofsted</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">: Children's social care inspections and outcomes</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">:</span></li></ol></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:14.4pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.65pt; text-align:justify"><a href="http://www.ofsted.gov.uk/resources/official-statistics-childrens-social-care-inspections-and-outcomes"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.ofsted.gov.uk/resources/official-statistics-childrens-social-care-inspections-and-</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:none">outcomes</span></a><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:none">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">These</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> show 72% of all homes are Good or Better - 16% Outstanding; 56% Good; 24% Adequate; 5% Inadequate</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 67.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The ICHA supports actions to ensure that ‘only Good is good enough’ and firm action on persistently Adequate or Inadequate homes. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It must be remembered that homes can be Inadequate and return to Good swiftly and the ICHA supports Ofsted in identifying actions for this recovery by all homes.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The DfE data pack dispels several myths that have gained credence</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The same range of quality applies to local authority and non-statutory homes (Page 20)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is no statistically significant correlation between a home's overall effectiveness and its size (page 21)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is no statistically significant correlation between number of homes owned and quality (page 22)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 65.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Ofsted report, Outstanding Providers, shows larger providers had a higher proportion of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Outstanding</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> ratings arising from their ability to invest in Quality Assurance. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The same could be offered to others</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> if commissioning was for more than placements but for support too. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Age of arrival and length of stay – raising concerns </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">All data from DfE data pack September 2013</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> 7% of looked-after children live in children’s homes (page 23) - the smallest number ever. </span></li></ol></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 66.76pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Is this the right number? </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 66.76pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">What factors have decreased its use?</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 66.76pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">What effects on specialism does this have?</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 66.76pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Why does England ha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ve less use </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">than other countries in the United Kingdom?</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 66.76pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Why is a children’s home the placement of first choice in many European  countries? </span></li><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The average age of young people in a children’s home is 14.6. (page 7)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.65pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Is this the best age to make optimum use of a placement? </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Where have they been before?</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Most young people are between 14 and 17. </span></li></ol></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.65pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Is a children’s home</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> only for adolescents? </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Why is there a wider spread of ages and especially younger ages</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in other countries? </span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">What happens to boys at age 10 that makes a children’s home placement suitable? </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Only 21% of young people stay in a children’s home longer than a year. (page 8). </span></li></ol></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.65pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Yet we know</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 80.91pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that continuity and stability are important.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 80.91pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">an upbringing and time to make and sustain relationships are vital for resilient young people.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 80.91pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">research findings – 2/3rds of young people with insecure and disorganised attachment profiles can become organised and insecure within</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> two years </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and with two further years can become more secure (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Kaniuk </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">et al</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">).</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 80.91pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We need to resist inappropriate normalisation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">often driven by cost</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> especially as the young person reaches 16.</span></li><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> 29% of young people will have had five or more placements before arriving at a children’s home. (Page 9)</span></li></ol></ul><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 78.11pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">What is making the 3+ and 5+ statistics rise annually?</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Is it identification, assessment, planning, or placement?</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 69pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">30.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Felt security is found to predict outcomes above stability.  The lived experience of stability, felt security and development of meaningful relationships matter to young people</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ICHA research review:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><a href="http://www.icha.org.uk/uploads/files/icha_research_review___stability_continuity_and_felt_security_sept_2011_1.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.icha.org.uk/uploads/files/icha_research_review___stability_continuity_and_felt_security_sept_2011_1.pdf</span></a></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 78.11pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Stability should be the default option but it is not as significant as felt security, continuity and social support. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The impact of these three is cumulative.  Continuity of relationships is key as it brings trusting relationships, sense of security and belonging, self-efficacy and hope. Stability may be a precondition for felt security but is not a sufficient factor. </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 86.05pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Distance as a factor in placement</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><a href="http://www.icha.org.uk/uploads/files/icha_research_review___placement_at_distance__from_home__jan__2012__1.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.icha.org.uk/uploads/files/icha_research_review___placement_at_distance__from_home__jan__2012__1.pdf</span></a></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">N.B. The DfE research ‘A long way from home’ of 2012 has not been made public. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">31.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Some children may need local placements and others more distant one</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  There may well be a ‘correct proportion’ but no one knows what it is and the proportion of local placements needed is certainly not 100%. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The evidence is clear that local placement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as a universal rule</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is the wrong conclusion.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">32.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We need to approach placement choice with the sophistication that includes instrumental and expressive (psychological, dynamic) dimensions. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In the main and where there is purpose, children are more able to accept additional, concerned and loving parental figures in their lives, with all the confusion inherent in such situations, than accept the loss of meaningful figures.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">33.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The decision on whether a child should be locally placed has to be a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">clinical</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> one that takes account of the relationship between child and family, the effect on the child of the local environment, and the purposes and quality of the placement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">34.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Simple instrumental factors such as distance between the placement and the child’s home are less important than the relationships among and the aspirations of care-givers in the placements’ (Lost in Care 1985).</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Out Of Authority placements</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">35.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Forthcoming research suggests that placements away from home are often made to secure specialist provision for children with complex disabilities or severe mental health issues, or to establish some geographical distance to break patterns of risky behaviour (child sexual exploitation, offending behaviour, gangs and guns).</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is nothing to say that being local increases knowledge and intelligence about the quality of homes or the suitability of their location. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Do we know if social work oversight is increased? Family work can be a task given successfully to the very skilled practitioners in this work in children’s homes. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is not only social workers who can do this task. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">36.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We need a clear definition of Out Of Authority. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Currently it can mean round the corner or over the road.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 67.65pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:462.1pt"><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.65pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Question – are we not at a point where we can say that children’s homes are offering a national service?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.65pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">We are now sharing a high-level needs service across the country. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">This has happened without strategy. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">If we now apply strategy to it</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">we might make better or even best use of this national service.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">It is not possible for any local authority to always meet all needs. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> We </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">should not be asking them to do so.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Location</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">37.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Government figures show that areas with a current density of homes (North West, West Midlands, Kent) have always had more homes. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This arises out of their historical development. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">38.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The picture is changing. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It will change more quickly if the Government had a national strategy for residential child care. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There are no current DfE proposals for this. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">39.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The change is complicated by new demands by some local authorities for planning permission for children’s homes.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> A recent debate in Parliament recorded that such hurdles are not supported by legislation. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">40.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Further requirements, such as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">any bureaucracy surrounding </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">safe area checks, will slow the changes desired by Government.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">41.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is no direct correlation between location of children's homes and level of deprivation. (page 38)</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">42.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The title of page 39, ‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is a slight skew towards deprived areas in the location of the 1,718 homes by local levels of crime and disorder’ requires more context</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as extracted from the source used by DfE The English Indices of Deprivation 2010</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">:</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.65pt; text-align:justify"><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/6320/1870718.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/6320/1870718.pdf</span></a></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 80.91pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">56 % of local authorities contain at least one LSOA (Lower Layer Super Output – local authority district level) that is amongst t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he 10% most deprived in England.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 80.91pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The choice of threshold to adopt</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in defining areas as ‘deprived’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is completely arbitrary (page 85)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 80.91pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">However, it is not possible to say, for example, that an LSOA with a score of 40 is twice as deprived as an LS</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">OA with a score of 20 (page 51).</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 80.91pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Districts can vary enormously. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Some contain more variation in deprivation while deprivation elsewhere may be concentrated in pockets rather than being more evenly spread. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This makes an overall picture more d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ifficult to establish (page 54).</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 80.91pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There are 6,496 LSOAs in the most deprived quintile in England and 10.2 million people live in these LSOAs – this represents almost exactly 20% of the population of England. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">However, not all people living in these LSOAs are deprived (page </span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">82)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 80.91pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">10.4 million people live in the least 20% of the deprived LSOAs – thi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s is 20.2% of the population of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">England. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Over one third (35.6%) of these least deprived LSOAs are in the South East. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 80.91pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The weighting of crime in the evaluations is 9.3%</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 67.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">43.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is no data</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> presented in the DfE data pack regarding the level of deprivation of local authorities and their use of homes. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Opportunity to do so was possible here and in pages 22 – 41. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This could be an informative study. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Costs</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">44.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The costs reported in the DfE data pack are extrap</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">olations from a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">limited sample.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">45.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The most accurate costs were collated by the National Centre for Excellence in Residential Child Care and Revolution Consulting</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> through an FOI to all local authorities. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">These figures </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">from 110 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">local authorities are the best information ever on this sector.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.65pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Private and voluntary average cost per week is £2,841</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.65pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Local </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">authority average cost per week</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is £2,490</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 67.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">46.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Comparative costings of local authority and other homes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is not advisable.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The two cohorts are not comparable, sizes and needs often diverge. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is also a likely under</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">costing of local authority homes.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> There is a need for a level playing field that can determine one method of calculating costs.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#454545; font-family:Helvetica; font-size:9pt">Kaniuk J, Steele M and Hodges J (2004) Report on a longitudinal research project exploring the development of attachments between older hard-to-place children and their adopters over the first two years of placement. Adoption and Fostering Journal, 28, 2, 61-67.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Munro, E.R., McDermid, S., Hollingworth, K. and Cameron, C. (forthcoming, 2013) Children’s homes: understanding the market and the use of out of authority placements. Research Brief. London: Childhood Wellbeing Research Centre.</span></p></body></html>